{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778549738,"nonce":"LR6VPt7kHQmfrTk6jgpd4VxLVe8=","message":"**Cross-cutting analyses lesson surfaced from `f47abb1` — when within/across pairwise RMSE ratios are (not) justified.**\n\nThe just-merged lit-replication 6-cell matrix (`f47abb1`, commits `b91b8b3` / `ceb3b87` / `8018e57`) initially used `within-cell vel RMSE / nearest-across-cell vel RMSE` as the PRIMARY decision metric (carried over from `baseline_jerk_vrnn_matrix` and the variance-metric resolution in comment #17 above). That choice produced a wrong-sign reading: every cell ratio \u003e 0.5, headlined as a \"negative result\" — when the underlying absolute within-cell RMSE numbers actually showed a strong positive finding (`lit__post_nojerk`: ~3× tighter than flat cells, ~10× less anticipation, plausible peak vel).\n\n**The pitfall.** A within/across ratio is justified only when:\n\n1. The conditions being compared are expected — on cost-function or task-structure grounds — to produce systematically different trajectories, AND\n2. The question being asked is whether replicates of one condition cluster tighter than the distance between conditions (i.e. an anchor-vs-conditions or generalisation framing).\n\nIf both hold, the across-cell denominator captures the *expected* inter-condition kinematic distance, and a ratio \u003c 1 means within-cell replicates cluster tighter than that expected scale — a meaningful normalisation.\n\nIf either fails — and specifically, when a matrix sweeps training-method variants where all cells are candidates for the same job, with no a priori expectation that any two cells produce different trajectories — the across-cell denominator just reflects whatever kinematic distance the cost-function manipulations happen to induce. A ratio near or above 1 then conveys nothing about within-cell quality; it just says within-cell variance is comparable to the kinematic distance between methodological variants, which can be true even when within-cell variance is excellent (the `f47abb1` `post_nojerk` cell has within-RMSE 0.036 m/s and ratio 1.09, because nearest-across-cell RMSE is also ~0.033).\n\n**Recommendation going forward.**\n\n- **Default to absolute within-cell RMSE (m/s) as the PRIMARY replicate-clustering metric** for training-method matrices and other \"same-job-candidate\" sweeps. Pair it with absolute kinematic metrics (hold drift in mm, peak velocity in m/s) for sanity.\n- **Use within/across pairwise ratios only when the experimental framing justifies them** — anchor-vs-conditions, generalisation, robustness probes where cells are designed to produce different trajectories and the question is \"do replicates of one condition cluster tighter than the inter-condition distance?\". Spell out that justification in the matrix pre-reg.\n- **CV (SD/mean of peak velocity) is fine as an auxiliary scalar** but does not replace the full-profile within-cell RMSE (see comments #16 / #17 above for the prior CV-vs-RMSE-ratio resolution; that resolution stands within its scope but does not require ratios as the default everywhere).\n- **Prior matrices**: where ratios were used appropriately (anchor-vs-conditions framing), they remain valid. Where they were used as the default without that justification (notably `f47abb1`), recheck the underlying absolute within-cell numbers before drawing sign-of-effect conclusions.\n\nCorrective comment on `f47abb1` (explicit retraction of the negative-result framing) and on `c99ad9d` (training-methods coord reading) have been posted. Doc + figure-spec correction lives on branch `feature/f47abb1-ratio-correction` (auth request `388d6576`).","files":null}]}